To assess the role of media reporting, @RoshaniyaLGBT  examined a wide sample of news broadcasts and publications‚Äîa total of 76 to be precise‚Äîfrom around the world to develop a news coverage index for media reporting on the plight of LGBT+ Afghans.

Roshaniya continues to challenge from its unique vantage point as the only LGBT+ Afghan organization, run by LGBT+ Afghans, and dedicated solely to humanitarian relief and asylum protection for LGBT+ Afghans.

Western NGOs such as Immigration Equality, OutRight Action International, Rainbow Railroad, and Stonewall continue to be given dominant coverage, often overshadowing the voices of LGBT+ Afghans in print, online, and on television.

A shining example being the coverage of the historic first LGBT+ Afghan protest, held in Pakistan, to demonstrate the UK‚Äôs refusal to grant asylum to over 1,000+ Afghans at risk from the Taliban, which was led by Ozlam, a Transgender Afghan refugee & Roshaniya‚Äôs Advocacy Officer.

LGBT+ Afghans are perceived less as helpless victims and represented more as actors who wield agency in bringing positive change for the rest of the community.
LGBT+ Afghans are now being regarded with more agency as @RoshaniyaLGBT activists amplify their voices and expand their sphere of influence internationally.

The portrayals of LGBT+ Afghans in most publications has focused solely on their misery. Roshaniya has discovered the depiction of LGBT+ Afghans is more rooted in presumptions and not fully grounded in the experience of members of the community.

Further, Roshaniya‚Äôs study showed that, too often, what western individuals and NGOs wrote failed to give adequate reportage of activist LGBT+ Afghan voices, despite the fact that LGBT+ Afghan activists are readily available to tell their own stories.

Not many media showed the solidarity of LGBT+ Afghans to form a community around Roshaniya (and the Behesht Collective) and work‚Äîas Human Rights Defenders‚Äîto help each other survive and escape Afghanistan.

For example, we found more instances of LGBT+ Afghans being portrayed as helpless victims at the mercy of foreigners to rescue them, with only a few instances showing their civic mobilization, courage, solidarity, and strength.
Our assessment shows the high rate of LGBT+ Afghans being portrayed as nondescript, passive, powerless, and weak victims across news platforms and sources.

As Afghanistan returns to the international spotlight with the one-year anniversary of the Taliban‚Äôs return, the Afghan LGBT+ network Roshaniya examines the portrayal of LGBT+ Afghans within news media around the globe.
